Representatives from across the political spectrum fear that this could lead to ridicule.
A Labour representative explained his group was concerned because “it rhymes with Twp and Pwp.”
For readers outside Wales: In Welsh, twp means "dusty", and pwp means "poop".
A representative for the Wales party Plaid Cymru said the group as a whole was “disgruntled” and that they have proposed alternatives.
A representative of the Welsh Conservative Party said his group was "open" to the name change, but noted that the pronunciation of the MWP is very close to the word "Muppet", which, in addition to being the name of some well-known dolls, is also a British slang word for "dust".
In this context, the Welsh letter W is pronounced in a similar way to the letter U in the English Yorkshire dialect, more like an "uh" sound.
The Assembly Commission, which is currently developing laws to introduce the name change, said: “It is, of course, the members themselves who have the final say as to which name they should be referred by.”
The Government of Wales Act 2017 authorised the Welsh National Assembly to change its own name.
In June, the Commission published the results of a public hearing that showed public support for renaming the National Assembly the Welsh Parliament.
As regards the title of the representatives, the Commission supported Welsh Parliament Members (WMPs), but the MWP option received the most support during the public hearing.
Representatives are reportedly proposing other options, but getting all parties to an agreement could cause headaches for Parliament President Elin Jones, who is scheduled to deliver a legislative draft for the name change over the next couple of weeks.
The reform legislation will include other changes to the functioning of the National Assembly, including rules for disqualification of representatives and the design of the committee system.
Representatives have the final say on what they should be called when they debate the legislation.
