This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a crucial skill children and young people are undoubtedly going to need in the future.
Language as a choice of subject is now valued at the same level as science as science, technology, engineering and mathematics on the curriculum for independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 per cent of the reasons employers reported having difficulty filling a vacancy were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important to prepare young people for a future career.
As more and more job opportunities require language skills, these skills become essential in a globalized world.
If you’ve learned a second language, these lifelong skills will provide real benefits in the future, no matter what career you choose.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language a double-digit number of participants (15 percent) could speak.
This is why investing in language learning is now crucial for today’s children.
Knowing more languages, especially those related to emerging economies, will give children better opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland if each school teach in different languages.
Many schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most valuable to the UK on the road to 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever interests your child, there will always be a choice of languages to choose from at independent schools, with teachers who are experts in this area.
Scottish independent schools aim to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the knowledge and skills they need to succeed, whatever the future brings.
It cannot be denied in today’s global business environment that languages are increasingly crucial to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Charter schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and distinction to Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Chair of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
