Ri reiterated well-known North Korean grievances against Washington’s opposition to a gradual denuclearization, in which North Korea is rewarded for gradual denuclearization steps, but his statement was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a sitting president of the United States and a North Korean leader, in which Kim pledged to work toward “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first,’ raising the pressure via sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposing the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” according to Ri.
“The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a pipe dream for people who know nothing about us.
