Harvard students take courses to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will help students get more sleep by tackling the growing culture of memorizing themselves through the night with caffeine drinks as fuel.
One academic found that students at the world’s best universities often had no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after he gave a lecture on the impact sleep deprivation has on learning.
“After the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why hasn’t anyone said this before?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to the students the importance of good sleep habits in order to perform academically and athletically, and for the general condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and CEO of the university’s health services, said the university decided to start the course after they saw students suffering from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for an hour, has a series of interactive assignments.
In one part there is a picture of a room in a dormitory, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books and hear about the effects of caffeine and light and how sporting performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important a sleep routine is.
In another part, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase their risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
“We are aware that this is not going to change student behaviour immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know about this, just as you have a right to know about the risks of smoking,” Professor Czeisler said.
There is still some pride in being able to memorize all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students led to sleep deprivation being a growing problem.
Enough and good sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said—even as a remedy against weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, leading to constant hunger pangs.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course, taking one of the professor’s classes last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course inspired him to work for a course that was available for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master’s students to take a similar program of study before enrolling in the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm for when to go to bed as well as for when to get up, and that they should be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic screens and LED lights. This type of light can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep problems.
