It has become a tradition now to look for Brexit allusions in every new film with a British slant and it seems to be appropriate for this revival of the parody franchise Johnny English action comedy – which started in 2003 with Johnny English and resurfaced in 2011 with Johnny English Reborn.
Will sarcastic self-satisfaction about how obviously hopeless we are to become the nation’s new export commodity?
In any case, the incompetent Johnny English with his bulging eyes and rubber face has had his license renewed to mess it up for the second time – his name says more than anything else that he is a clear and comic figure intended for territories with non-English speaking cinema audiences.
He is, of course, the silly secret agent who, despite his bizarre James Bond ambitions, is a mix of Clouseau, a dash of Mr Bean, and a portion of that guy who contributes a single note to the fire wagon-themed music segment at the opening ceremony of the 2012 London Olympics.
