English is snapped back to Whitehall for a quick briefing and reunited with his old, tormented helper Bough, played by Ben Miller.
Bough is now a married man, spliced with a submarine commander, a hysterical upper-class lady role where Vicki Pepperdine is a little wasted.
So the Batman and Robin style of messing everything up on a mission for the Queen is back, where they confront Olga Kurylenko’s amazing femme fatale, Ophelia Bulletova.
Meanwhile, the prime minister is seduced by the charismatic tech billionaire who claims he can solve Britain’s cyber problems: the insidious Jason Volta, played by Jake Lacy.
English and Bough start their journey with farcical escapades: disguised as waiters, they set fire to a flashy French restaurant, wreaking havoc while hiding aboard Volta’s luxury yacht; and English unleashes sheer anarchy as he attempts to use a VR headset to make his mark in Volta’s house.
All the stops are really pulled out before the last sequence, but even as amiable and noisy it is so there is a lot that reminds of children's TV with the whole thing.
Pretty mediocre, all of it.
And as with the other Johnny English films, I couldn’t help but think: can the British film industry give Rowan Atkinson a role where he really gets to use his talent?
