Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt inferior in terms of sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to everyone because of his sexuality – but it gave him the motivation he needed to succeed.
The 24-year-old said it wasn’t until high school that he realized he wasn’t like everyone else.
In the first program Desert Island Discs on Radio 4 presented by Lauren Laverne, he said that he stood up for the rights of homosexuals to give others “hope”.
He also said that becoming a parent made him care less about winning the Olympics.
The regular host of the traditional program, Kirsty Young, will be away for a few months due to illness.
Daley appeared a little lost on Laverne's first broadcast and said he felt "less valuable" than everyone else he grew up with because "it was not socially acceptable to like both boys and girls".
To this day, it is these feelings of being inferior and different that have been the real motivation and have me the power and strength to succeed.
He wanted to prove that he “was something,” he said, so he wouldn’t disappoint everyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
He is a two-time bronze medalist in the Olympics and has become a high-profile LGBT ambassador. He used his participation at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to appeal for more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he’s coming forward because he feels lucky to be able to live openly without negative consequences and wants to give others “hope.”
The three-time world champion said that falling in love with a man – filmmaker Dustin Lance Black from the United States, whom he met in 2013 – “surprised me.”
Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him, last year, but he said the age difference had never been a problem.
“When you’re going through so much at such a young age” — he attended his first Olympics when he was 14, and his father died of cancer three years later — he said it was tough to find someone the same age who had experienced similar ups and downs.
The couple became parents in June to a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "whole perspective" had been changed.
“If you asked me last year, it was all about me winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know, there are bigger things than a gold medal in the Olympics.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie".
The son has the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept his death, and one of the last things he asked was if they had bought tickets for London 2012 – since he wanted to sit in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him he wouldn’t live long enough to sit in the front row,” he said.
“I held his hands when he stopped breathing, and it wasn’t until he actually stopped breathing and was dead that I finally realized he wasn’t invincible,” he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
“I just knew that this was what I had dreamed of all my life – diving in front of a home crowd at the Olympics, the best feeling ever,” he said.
It also inspired his first song selection – Proud by Heather Small – which meant a lot to him in the run-up to the Olympics and still gives him goosebumps.
Desert Island Discs airs on BBC Radio 4 Sundays at 11:15 BST.
