Germany's new warship delayed once again
The German Navy’s newest frigate should have been completed in 2014 to replace Cold War-era warships, but that won’t happen until at least next year due to failing systems and galloping costs, local media reported.
The completion of the Rhineland-Palatinate, the lead ship of the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quoted a military spokesperson.
The vessel was to have been handed over to the Navy in 2014, but the major problems after delivery pursued the ambitious project.
The four vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class navy ordered as far back as 2007, will replace the old frigates of the Bremen-class.
It has been agreed that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a variety of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – it should be possible to use the latest frigates for up to two years away from home port.
Constant delays mean, however, that the advanced warships – they were said to give Germany strength at sea – will already be outdated by the time they are put into service, Die Zeit reports.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of important "software and hardware defects" that rendered the warship useless in a combat mission.
The software defects were particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels were to be operated by a crew of around 120 sailors – only half of the crew of older Bremen-class frigates.
It was also revealed that the ship has an enormous overweight, which reduces performance and limits the Navy's ability to make upgrades in the future.
The 7,000-ton "Rhineland-Palatinate" is estimated to be twice as heavy as similar ships of the same class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the price tag on the entire project – including crew training – has also started to become a problem.
It is claimed to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros – from the original 2.2 billion euros.
The problems surrounding the new frigates are of particular importance in light of recent warnings that Germany’s naval strength is shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German government’s defense committee, confirmed that the navy is indeed “running out of usable ships.”
The official said the problem has escalated over time because old ships were decommissioned, but no new vessels arrived.
He regrets that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could be used by the Navy.
National Trust eavesdrops on the secret life of bats
New research carried out at a country estate in the Scottish Highlands aims to uncover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help design future conservation measures.
The study by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brown-eared and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also perform mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Experts’ audio analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat droppings and which species do what.
A habitat map and a report will then be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, conservation advisor to the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will be included in the decision on what measures should be introduced, such as the construction of pastures and how best to take care of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction works that affect breeding sites and habitat reduction.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with flypaper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from house cats.
Bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road as they fly.
The NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out surveys, survey breeding sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only separate bat sanctuary at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten species of bat.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have the perfect area for bats,” he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of mapping the bats before maintenance is carried out on a property, since inadvertent destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young, and perhaps wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected, and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them, or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish staffer for the Bat Conservation Trust, has called on the public to help in the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species, we simply don’t know how the populations are coping.”
