Europe regained the throne when the team of Danish team captain Thomas Bjørn got the 14.5 points they needed to beat the United States.
US star Phil Mickelson, who struggled during much of the tournament, hit his tee shot in the water at the par-3 16th hole, and had to be beaten by Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari was brilliant on all his rounds and became 1 of 4 golfers who have ever gone 5-0-0 since the tournament got its current layout in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was knocked out 5 and 4 by the lowest ranked player on the European team, Thorbjørn Olesen from Denmark.
The world’s top-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2-1 to Ian Poulter of England, who may have played his last Ryder Cup final.
With eight Ryder Cups behind him, Sergio Garcia became the most successful European player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I can’t help it.
It's been a rough year.
I am so grateful that Thomas picked me out and had faith in me.
I’m very, very happy to have the cup back.
It’s about the team and I’m glad I could be of help,” said an emotional Garcia after the European win.
He hands the baton over to his compatriot John Ram, who beat American golf legend Tiger Woods 2 and 1 in singles play on Sunday.
“I’m incredibly proud to beat Tiger Woods – I followed that man closely growing up,” said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four of his games in France and now has a record of 13-21-3 career points in the Ryder Cup.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest golfers ever, who has won 14 major titles, beaten only by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA struggled all weekend to find the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played golf with high precision throughout the tournament.
U.S. team captain Jim Furyk, after a disappointing performance for his squad, said, "I'm proud of these guys, they fought.
There were moments this morning when we put pressure on Europe.
We threw up.
Hats off to Thomas.
He's a great team captain.
All 12 of his players played very well.
We will regroup, I will work with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup committee and will look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I’m proud to be their team captain.
You just have to take your hat off.
We were beaten.”
Update on algal bloom: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows an overall decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County — suggesting reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algae extends about 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots are detected about 10 miles (16 km) off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported on or off the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory tract irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in Florida’s northwest last week.
